#Text=Dengiz Beg Rumlu

#Text=Dengiz Beg Rumlu [ lower-alpha 1 ] ( died 1613 ) was a Turkoman courtier from the Rumlu tribe , who served as merchant-envoy to Habsburg Spain during the reign of Safavid king ( shah ) Abbas I ( r.1588 – 1629 ) .
#Text=Biography

#Text=In late 1609 , Abbas I sent the Portuguese diplomat and missionary Antonio de Gouvea ( now in Safavid service ) back to Spain and Rome in order to construct an alliance against the common enemy ; the Ottoman Turks . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]
#Text=Dengiz Beg Rumlu , merchant by profession , was assigned to accompany de Gouvea as merchant-envoy with some 100 bales of raw silk . [ 1 ] [ 2 ]

#Text=At the Spanish court of Philip III ( r.1598 – 1621 ) , where they arrived in 1611 , a major misunderstanding arose ; Dengiz Beg had sold more than half of the total bales of silk for his own profit . [ 1 ] [ 3 ] [ lower-alpha 2 ] De Gouvea , without any sort of compromise with the Iranian government , suddenly offered the remaining number of silk bales as a gift to the Spanish king , even though the Iranians had intended to sell them as a sample of the silk they intended to deliver in the future . [ 1 ]
#Text=De Gouvea and Dengiz secured a trade agreement with Philip III , but it proved to be of no value for the Spanish government never adopted it . [ 5 ]
#Text=They also urged for a blockade of the Red Sea , but they were reportedly " no more successful " in this than Robert Shirley . [ 5 ]

#Text=Conform Abbas I 's desire , at the Spanish court , Dengiz Beg Rumlu supported the elevation of de Gouvea to the rank of bishop of Cyrene and Apostolic vicar of the Armenians of the royal capital of Isfahan . [ 1 ] [ 5 ]
#Text=Dengiz Beg and de Gouvea set sail for Safavid Iran from Lisbon in March 1612 with gifts and presents from the Habsburg crown . [ 6 ] [ 7 ]
#Text=Dengiz Beg received a coat of mail and a specific sword which he himself had requested from Philip III . [ 8 ]
#Text=He also received a gold chain , a gold sword , a portrat of Philip III decorated with numerous costly gems , as well as some horse trappings which he liked to have . [ 8 ]
#Text=In the spring of 1613 , Dengiz Beg appeared at the Iranian court . [ 9 ]
#Text=Reportedly , as he went down on his knees to kiss the king 's foot , Abbas kicked him and ordered for his execution . [ 9 ]
#Text=It appears that king Abbas had appointed a person in Dengiz 's suite to spy on him in Europe , for Abbas was already aware of Dengiz 's wrongdoings before his presentation at court . [ 10 ]
#Text=Amongst others , Dengiz Beg was accused of treating the members of his mission extremely bad ; this had resulted in some of them converting to Christianity and staying in Europe . [ 4 ]
#Text=Abbas ' anger with Dengiz Beg was most likely increased by Philip III 's meager responses and actions and for " reawakening " his dissatisfaction with the Portuguese occupation of Hormuz .
#Text=When Abbas then also found out that the silk had been given to Philip III as a gift rather than being sold , he became furious . [ 4 ]

#Text=When Abbas later received de Gouvea , he also discovered that Dengiz Beg had received nothing of equal value in return ; the presents and goods were all a gift , and not payment for the silk ; and they were , reportedly , not even nearly as costly as the bales of silk that de Gouvea had given to Philip III . [ 11 ] [ 6 ]
#Text=Dengiz Beg was executed in 1613 . [ 1 ] [ 12 ]
#Text=It remains unclear what the precise reason was ; it may be that his role in the " silk affair " proved to be the straw that broke the camel 's back . [ 1 ]
